The XRD patterns revealed noticeable changes in the structures of the materials after the reactions (Fig. 8). In the reaction using sodium oxalate solution, the material presented 2θ peaks at 43.5° and 50.5°, corresponding to planes (111) and (200), respectively, related to metallic copper (JCPDS 04-0836), together with peaks centered at 2θ of 36.5° and 61.0°, related to Cu2O, showing that after 24 h the material had undergone a reduction process. On the other hand, when the reaction was performed using KBrO3 or NaOH solutions, or pure water, the materials showed diffraction peaks related to copper carbonate (malachite, CuCO3.Cu(OH)2) (JCPDS 01-0959). In fact, the first evidence of reaction of CO2 with CuO was a color change from brown to light green, indicative of copper carbonate formation32,33:6\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
